caption:
It's been a very long time since I've uploaded any of the progress from our current project. 

For the pathway we have used recycled pammets from the property. Laid in an arts and crafts style, we used soft red brick to lay the outline of the path which gives the area a clear definition. Infilled with pammets in a diamond pattern pointed up using traditional sand and cement pointing. For the herring bone patterns we used all of the remaining excess from cuts etc, used a soft red brick as a template and marked them up to cut. It was a very time consuming process but the end result was fantastic. The herringbone areas will be pointed using kiln dried sand. 

The hard standing area which has been done completely in soft red brick is for a bin storage area, hence the three different areas for each bin and then the herringbone stretch to signify the walkway. 

Planting beds have been outlined using 5mm steel edging. We are now in the process of refilling the beds after being dug to the depth of 600mm.

We are getting very close to the end of this project and am very excited to see the end result!!

#landscaping #landscape #gardendesign #restoration #brickwork #herringbone #suffolklandscapes #suffolk #driveway #garden

caption:
Haven't uploaded in a long time so here are one of the smaller projects we've completed recently.

The clients had this block paving installed during COVID and because of that a lot of the materials weren't available.

It had become really unlevel where roots etc had grown underneath because it had no subbase.

So we ripped out the old and installed new sandstone paving throughout.

This was to help create a level space throughout the garden to help with accessibility for wheelchair use in the future. 

We reinstated the original steps with new bullnosed coping with mitred corners etc, they were hand cut using a grinder which was a first for me and definitely harder then it looks to get the cuts perfect so all the joint lines are equally spaced top and bottom.

We also installed a bespoke made stand for the water butt to sit on using left over material we had which matched in with the rest of the paving. 

The curves where to match the existing beds and the clients where really happy with the work and we wi
ll be returning soon to pave another area.

caption:
Another completed project.

Steel is becoming more of a sort after product in gardens for its longevity compared to its counterparts such as timber.

This project we replaced 4 sleeper beds with 3mm mild steel laser cut to specification by Yarmouth steel.

Very tricky project with the tight spaces as we didn't want to disturb the existing planting area or adjacent structures ie fences.

While there we discovered that the pergola leading to the garden area all the supporting posts had rotted all the way through leaving it an extremely vulnerable and hazardous structure.

We supported existing timber with concrete supports and then boxed in the concrete with timber to keep the aesthetics consistent thoughtout.

On the other side of the property again we had rotten oak uprights as a feature which we cut the rot off, drilled a hole into the bottom of the uprights then concreted some threaded rod and then sat our uprights on top giving the same feature but with all of the timber sitting out of the ground.

Very interesting project, really enjoyed working on this and can't wait to get back and see how the steel beds have rusted!

I think there's going to be plenty more steel work in the future

caption:
This little project in Stutton was a really fun project although small and simple it had a lot of different details that made it interesting throughout.

The client wanted an area which felt secluded from the rest of the garden and screening to hide all utility areas. 

They specified for trellis so they can grow different Jasmine's and Clematis to create a stunning screen. 

I wanted to add some detail to the posts to compliment the trellis and I think we managed that very well. There's a picture to show the difference in the posts before and after. They were so happy with all of it that they asked for me trellis through the project!

The client specified they wanted a seating area in the top corner which is were the garden had most of the sun throughout the day so we built a raised area using clay pavers and then infilled with a herringbone design. With a pathway leading to the utility area from the top.

We then built the arts and crafts pathway running through the middle of the garden to the clients specifications. Using old clay tiles, clay pavers and sandstone paving. It was a fun experience putting our own ideas forward for some creative styles.

Definitely a big learning curve for things you can do for some arts and crafts work.

Edged in 5mm steel to show the borders of the planting areas.

We will be returning to this l
Project in the next couple of months to plant up which I'm very excited for!

caption:
Photos from our latest project.

Incredible design by @fredericwhyte as per usual.

A clever use of a very small space,  keeping practicality in mind but focusing on aesthetics. 

The use of corten steel pilings to provide a screen between the utility area and the garden area has worked even better than expected, with clever planting to really enhance the privacy without feeling closed in. 

We have moved all utilities to the other end of the garden and leveled off a concrete pad which fits all 3 bins and the shed which frees up all of the space at the bottom of the property to be garden space to relax in.

Beforehand it was a bank of soil that ran up to the fence line so everything had to be taken up a step with bins behind one and other which for every day use just seemed excessive and unnecessary. Also didn't look tidy at all.

We've boxed the oil tank off installing a discreet gate within the fence line to allow for easier access into both ends of the added storage area.

Removing the shed we were then able to bring heights up to have a nice level space behind the corten steel screening.

Really excited to return in the summer once all the planting has established.

caption:
We've started the dig out on our latest Frostenden project. 

The aim is to create a low maintenance garden subtly hiding all the day to day utilities of the household such as bin storage, oil tank and general storage.

During the excavation we have found old pathways which will be kept and mended where necessary to create unique features throughout. 

The barn will be used for a mechanics area so access and good working space will be provided while complementing and screening with cleverly designed planting areas. 

A formal walk way will be built leading to the back door using recycled materials from site. 

A well has been uncovered and will be reinstated and used as a planting area. 

Looking forward to getting stuck into this project!! 

As always amazing designs by @fredericwhyte

caption:
Just some quick before pictures of the current project we are on. These are all prior to any work taking place.

Previous contractors have done a pretty bad job prior so clients have asked for us to come in and put things right.

So just a little insight, all the paving had been laid with insufficient and incorrect fall resulting in pooling water causing damp in and around the garden. All paving has been removed and the lower terrace is being relayed using the same paving.

The previous contractor had used no primer for the porcelain tiles resulting in some popping up and staining happening. Joint lines where out of square and different sizes. 

The bifold doors have a cavity underneath above the damp course which was folded over and had cement pushed on top of the paving to keep it there and then painted black also some sections had expanding foam sprayed under and others didn't. So the damp course underneath was basically pointless 

The drains where filled with concrete.

The lower terrace had soil underneath the cement for the paving with some rubble all on top of a concrete pad.

There was nowhere for water to travel in this garden and nothing can breathe, pair that with a completely shaded corner turned this terraced garden into a breeding ground for unwanted algae. (As you can see from the photos which was 2 months between them being taken how quickly it comes)

All over it was actually quite disheartening to see the work that had been done and someone thought it was acceptable. 

Another design done by @fredericwhyte 

Look forward to showing you everything that's taken place so far and everything to come.

Also would like to mention that this project has no outside access and everything that is done has to come through the house which has all recently been done so there's a little pressure there!!

caption:
Not the best photos to showcase the work on this project so far.

Most of the work taken place has been soil preparation based for large planting areas for perennial planting. 

We installed steel edging to replace existing timber edging which had rotted away and installed some shingle around service access points to tidy up the area. 

When we started excavating the site it was basically rubble for 3-400mm depth. 

Some very interesting treasures found such as very old bricks, axe heads and various others.

The weather caused no end of problems.

We will be returning to this site after the planting has been completed to finish off final levels and some freshly laid turf. Very excited for the end result of this one.

caption:
I don't think I uploaded much to do with the front of this project as it was mainly a waste storage area for the majority of the project.

Here we have the final results. 

We will be coming back to finish off with a layer of mulch to help tidy things up and the sanding and painting of the fences out the front. 

Really happy with how the front turned out as for the majority of the project I couldn't see anything but piles of type 1 and soil, but we got there!!

caption:
Really happy to be able to give an update for the new year so far.

So from the last update we've finished most of the hardcore levels around the site, worked where we need to adjust heights in the future so we are ready for the paving etc.

Our main focus has been this fence, definitely been a bit of a challenge when dealing with the neighbours on this project so we've just decided to go Infront of fences and 1.8m in height all around.

This has been difficult because we've tried to meet the heights of existing fences etc and then meet up with our new heights.

Really happy with how it's turned out, little details like the mitred transition when you go from the Terrace down to the planting area which will be seen just in front of the rendered clockwork.

@fredericwhyte has been really clever with the design utilising different sizes of timber for the upright slats as to create an illusion of the space feeling larger in the garden as you progress from larger slats to smaller slats down the fence line. (200mmx25-150mmx25-100mmx25) it's hard to get the impact this has created from the pictures.

caption:
So close to finishing up this project.

As you can probably tell by the state of everything, it's been the messiest project I've done for a while the clay was a nightmare.

Really happy with the finished result of the work, unfortunately we weren't able to level the whole garden and make everything else square but what can you do!! 

As stated around the patio the clients have said they'd like to rearrange beds and heights etc and the soil left on site will be moved around when we grout up. 

Definitely a job where everything came together at the end. Always a challenge to work with new products that you haven't used before but if you're not thinking you're not learning.

caption:
Update on the hard landscaping for the current project taking place.

We have the retaining wall in for the terraced area at the rear of the property. The measurements of the terraced area had to be adapted to accommodate for existing underground services, so everything was brought forward which has now allowed for the retaining wall and coping to cover up the existing foundation for the conservatory which was an eyesaw, so has all worked out quite well.

Brick/block work for all the steps bar 1 at the front of the property have been completed and filled ready for the stone to be laid.

 2/3 bullnose steps have been laid in the rear and 1/2 have been laid in The front of the property.

 The paving that is being used is supplied by @_londonstone and it's a heath sandstone, some really stunning detail in the stone as you can see from some of the photos. It's beautiful when you can get the flow of one pattern lead from one paving stone to the other. 

The paving design was set out by @fredericwhyte
as always it's coming together fantastically as expected with his designs.

The paving is being laid at a 1:80 ratio fall which is 45mm for the distance of the terraced area.

Ducting has been put in for up lights places by various trees that will be in the garden. 

As always the project is coming together really well, really exciting to be working with such stunning products and working with a designer who has a clear image of what he wants. 

Really enjoying this and can't wait to see the finish line but don't at the same time as I'm enjoying the build.

caption:
A nice little return to the ongoing project in Yoxford. 

This has been an absolute favourite of mine to work on, some really great experience from this one.

Finished off the piers for the wall, with some custom made capping which was cut onsite myself. Really happy with how they turned out an incredibly smart finish for a first time try with 45 degree cuts on stone. Really proud moment!!

Steel edging has gone in to define the borders of planting areas and pathways.

Old reclaimed pavers from the garden have been cleaned up and re-used as features among the pathways. 

Really looking forward to Monday!
